<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,673,1082]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[888,1032,673,697]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Wingspan 11.0–17.0 mm. Adults of this genus as well as 
<taxonomicName authority="Zimmerman" authorityName="Zimmerman" authorityYear="1958" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Lantanophaga" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1193,1373,706,730]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Lantanophaga</emphasis>
Zimmerman
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Zimmerman" authorityName="Zimmerman" authorityYear="1958" box="[1061,1388,738,762]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Anstenoptilia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1061,1225,738,762]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Anstenoptilia</emphasis>
Zimmerman
</taxonomicName>
, are recognized by a distinct termen on both lobes 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,306,808,830]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Figure 1.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zeller" baseAuthorityYear="1871" box="[316,596,808,829]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Lioptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="albistriolatus">
<emphasis box="[316,596,808,829]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Lioptilodes albistriolatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
adult resting on larval and with fringe scales along the second lobe host plant, 
<taxonomicName box="[318,559,837,858]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Baccharis" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="halimifolia">
<emphasis box="[318,559,837,858]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Baccharis halimifolia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. termen forming a scalloped or tri-lobed margin. A faint triangular mark is present along the costa near the cleft base. The anal fringes of the hindwing third lobe also bear a distinct dark scale tuft. Males of this species are distinguishable from 
<taxonomicName authority="(Felder and Rogenhoffer)" baseAuthorityName="Felder and Rogenhoffer" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[819,1440,930,954]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Stenoptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taprobanes">
<emphasis box="[819,1126,930,954]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Stenoptilodes taprobanes</emphasis>
(Felder and Rogenhoffer)
</taxonomicName>
by genitalia only. The aedeagus and uncus are both slender and proportionally longer in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zeller" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[1267,1440,962,986]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Stenoptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipennis">
<emphasis box="[1267,1440,962,986]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">S. brevipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
compared to 
<emphasis box="[351,527,994,1018]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Felder and Rogenhoffer" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[351,523,994,1018]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Stenoptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taprobanes">S. taprobanes</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
Females can be easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Felder and Rogenhoffer" baseAuthorityYear="1875" box="[1053,1221,994,1018]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Stenoptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="taprobanes">
<emphasis box="[1053,1221,994,1018]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">S. taprobanes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by external characters, in this case the presence of a pair of distinct dark scale tufts on the ventral surface, flanking the ostium.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,1121,1274]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,367,1121,1145]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Life History.</emphasis>
Larvae feed on the shoots and flower buds of certain genera of 
<taxonomicName box="[1157,1347,1122,1146]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Plantaginaceae</taxonomicName>
includ- ing 
<taxonomicName authority="Ruiz &amp; Pav." authorityName="Ruiz &amp; Pav." box="[239,543,1154,1178]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Mecardonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[239,385,1154,1178]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Mecardonia</emphasis>
Ruiz &amp; Pav.
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[555,665,1154,1177]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Scoparia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[555,665,1154,1177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Scoparia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L., 
<taxonomicName authority="Aubl." authorityName="Aubl." box="[713,880,1154,1178]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Bacopa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[713,803,1154,1177]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Bacopa</emphasis>
Aubl.
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Jacq. Nickrent et al. (1988)" authorityName="Jacq. Nickrent" authorityYear="1988" box="[946,1392,1154,1178]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Russelia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[946,1051,1154,1178]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Russelia</emphasis>
Jacq. 
<bibRefCitation author="Nickrent, D. L. &amp; W. H. Eshbaugh &amp; T. K. Wilson" box="[1129,1392,1154,1178]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" refId="ref7893" refString="Nickrent, D. L., W. H. Eshbaugh, and T. K. Wilson. 1988. The vascular flora of Andros Island, Bahamas. Kendall / Hunt Publishing Company; Dubuque, Iowa. 211 p." type="book" year="1988">Nickrent et al. (1988)</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
list one of the host species, 
<taxonomicName box="[482,691,1186,1209]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Bacopa" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="monnieri">
<emphasis box="[482,691,1186,1209]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Bacopa monnieri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(L.) Pennell as occurring on 
<collectingRegion box="[1046,1134,1186,1210]" country="Bahamas" name="South Andros" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Andros</collectingRegion>
and include 
<taxonomicName box="[1294,1440,1186,1210]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Mecardonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1294,1440,1186,1210]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Mecardonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[246,351,1218,1242]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Plantaginaceae" genus="Russelia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Lamiales" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[246,351,1218,1242]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Russelia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as other taxa occurring elsewhere in 
<collectingCountry box="[813,980,1218,1242]" name="Bahamas" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
. Larvae and pupae are described and illustrated by 
<bibRefCitation author="Matthews, D. L." box="[366,577,1249,1274]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" refId="ref7316" refString="Matthews, D. L. 2006. Larvae and pupae of Nearctic Pterophoridae: A synopsis of life histories, morphology, and taxonomy (Lepidoptera: Pterophoroidea). Unpublished PhD Dissertation. University of Florida; Gainesville. 959 p." type="book" year="2006">Matthews (2006)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,1313,1434]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,372,1313,1337]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species is widespread in the Neotropical Region but previously unknown from 
<collectingCountry name="Bahamas" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">the Bahamas</collectingCountry>
. In the southeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[570,740,1346,1370]" name="United States of America" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">United States</collectingCountry>
it has been recorded from 
<collectingRegion box="[1064,1154,1346,1370]" country="United States of America" name="Florida" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Florida</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion box="[1213,1356,1346,1370]" country="United States of America" name="Mississippi" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Mississippi</collectingRegion>
. In the West Indies, it is known from 
<collectingCountry box="[573,641,1378,1402]" name="Cuba" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Cuba</collectingCountry>
, Guadeloupe, Martinique, 
<collectingCountry box="[975,1123,1378,1402]" name="Puerto Rico" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Puerto Rico</collectingCountry>
, and 
<collectingCountry box="[1192,1300,1378,1402]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bigot, L. &amp; J. Etienne" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="463 - 467" refId="ref7004" refString="Bigot, L., and J. Etienne. 2009. Les Pterophoridae de L'ile de la Guadeloupe (Lepidoptera). Bulletin de la Societe Entomologique de France 114 (4): 463 - 467." type="journal article" year="2009">Bigot and Etienne 2009</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Gielis, C." box="[371,514,1409,1434]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 290" refId="ref7152" refString="Gielis, C. 2006. Review of the Neotropical species of the family Pterophoridae, part I: Ochyroticinae, Deutercopinae, Pterophorinae (Platyptiliini, Exelastini, Oxyptilini) (Lepidoptera). Zoologische Mededelingen, Leiden 80 - 2 (1): 1 - 290." type="journal article" year="2006">Gielis 2006</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="3" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[192,1440,1473,1626]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,347,1473,1497]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Comments.</emphasis>
The female specimen from 
<collectingRegion box="[679,846,1474,1498]" country="Bahamas" name="North Andros" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">North Andros</collectingRegion>
(
<figureCitation box="[861,945,1474,1498]" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="5.[193,277,1399,1421]" captionTargetBox="[192,1440,192,1377]" captionTargetId="figure-226@5.[192,1440,192,1377]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Figure 2. Pterophoridae from North Andros Island: a) Lioptilodes albistriolatus; b) Stenoptilodes brevipennis; c) Sphenarches anisodactylus; d) Exelastis pumilio; e) Adaina perplexus; f) A. sp." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5174338" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5174338/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">Fig. 2b</figureCitation>
) is exceptionally worn but with the geni- tal scale tufts intact, allowing the identification. 
<bibRefCitation author="Matthews, D. L. &amp; R. A. Watkins" box="[787,1158,1506,1530]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="175 - 177" refId="ref7689" refString="Matthews, D. L., and R. A. Watkins. 2011. Extralimital records of the sage plume moth, Anstenoptilia marmarodactyla (Lepidoptera: Pterophoridae). Southern Lepidopterists' News 33 (4): 175 - 177." type="journal article" year="2011">Matthews and Watkins (2011)</bibRefCitation>
illustrate the forewing of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Zeller" baseAuthorityYear="1874" box="[223,399,1538,1562]" class="Insecta" family="Pterophoridae" genus="Stenoptilodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevipennis">
<emphasis box="[223,399,1538,1562]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="3">S. brevipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in comparison with similar species. Illustrations of both male and female genitalia are included in 
<bibRefCitation author="Gielis, C." box="[384,543,1569,1594]" pageId="4" pageNumber="3" pagination="1 - 290" refId="ref7152" refString="Gielis, C. 2006. Review of the Neotropical species of the family Pterophoridae, part I: Ochyroticinae, Deutercopinae, Pterophorinae (Platyptiliini, Exelastini, Oxyptilini) (Lepidoptera). Zoologische Mededelingen, Leiden 80 - 2 (1): 1 - 290." type="journal article" year="2006">Gielis (2006)</bibRefCitation>
. The specimen examined was spotted with a head lamp and netted while flying in low vegetation.
</paragraph>
